<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1436,937,1933]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
Six species are included in the 
<taxonomicName box="[505,630,938,961]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paeminosa">
<emphasis box="[505,630,938,961]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Paeminosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Group: 
<taxonomicName box="[734,890,938,961]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paeminosa">
<emphasis box="[734,890,938,961]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">H. paeminosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<collectingCountry box="[907,998,937,961]" name="Guyana" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Guyana</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1011,1123,937,961]" name="Suriname" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Suriname</collectingCountry>
), 
<taxonomicName box="[1143,1284,937,961]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="boliviana">
<emphasis box="[1143,1284,937,961]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">H. boliviana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<collectingCountry box="[1300,1388,937,961]" name="Bolivia" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
), 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="xingu">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">H. xingu</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<collectingCountry box="[227,301,973,997]" name="Brazil" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Brazil</collectingCountry>
), 
<taxonomicName box="[320,479,973,997]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="duohamata">
<emphasis box="[320,479,973,997]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">H. duohamata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[493,614,973,997]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="172" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="venezuela">
<collectingCountry box="[493,614,973,997]" name="Venezuela" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
</taxonomicName>
), 
<taxonomicName box="[632,780,973,997]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="punctilata">
<emphasis box="[632,780,973,997]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">H. punctilata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<collectingCountry box="[794,868,973,997]" name="Brazil" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Brazil</collectingCountry>
), and 
<taxonomicName box="[933,1050,973,997]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="neblina">
<emphasis box="[933,1050,973,997]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">H. neblina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[1065,1187,973,997]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="172" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="venezuela">
<collectingCountry box="[1065,1187,973,997]" name="Venezuela" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
</taxonomicName>
). Species in this group are moderately large to large (ca. 
<quantity box="[532,700,1009,1033]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.78" metricValueMax="1.96" metricValueMin="1.6" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" unit="mm" value="1.78" valueMax="1.96" valueMin="1.6">1.60–1.96 mm</quantity>
), coarsely punctate, and have a characteristic habitus (
<figureCitation box="[1314,1423,1009,1033]" captionStart-0="FIGURE 3" captionStart-1="FIGURE 4" captionStart-2="FIGURE 5" captionStart-3="FIGURE 6" captionStart-4="FIGURE 7" captionStart-5="FIGURE 8" captionStartId-0="72.[151,250,1650,1673]" captionStartId-1="73.[151,250,1650,1673]" captionStartId-2="74.[151,250,1650,1673]" captionStartId-3="75.[151,250,1650,1673]" captionStartId-4="76.[151,250,1650,1673]" captionStartId-5="77.[151,250,1612,1635]" captionTargetBox-0="[227,1366,208,1616]" captionTargetBox-1="[281,1320,212,1606]" captionTargetBox-2="[235,1350,193,1627]" captionTargetBox-3="[256,1330,193,1626]" captionTargetBox-4="[285,1308,218,1613]" captionTargetBox-5="[226,1357,193,1591]" captionTargetId-0="figure@72.[208,1379,193,1629]" captionTargetId-1="figure@73.[251,1335,193,1629]" captionTargetId-2="figure@74.[235,1351,193,1629]" captionTargetId-3="figure@75.[256,1330,193,1629]" captionTargetId-4="figure@76.[268,1318,193,1629]" captionTargetId-5="figure@77.[226,1360,193,1591]" captionTargetPageId-0="72" captionTargetPageId-1="73" captionTargetPageId-2="74" captionTargetPageId-3="75" captionTargetPageId-4="76" captionTargetPageId-5="77" captionText-0="FIGURE 3. Hydraena paeminosa, holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, and venter." captionText-1="FIGURE 4. Hydraena boliviana, holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, and venter." captionText-2="FIGURE 5. Hydraena xingu, holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, and venter." captionText-3="FIGURE 6. Hydraena duohamata, holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, and venter." captionText-4="FIGURE 7. Hydraena punctilata, holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, and venter." captionText-5="FIGURE 8. Hydraena neblina, holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, and venter." httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/1050066/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/1050068/files/figure.png" httpUri-2="https://zenodo.org/record/1050070/files/figure.png" httpUri-3="https://zenodo.org/record/1050072/files/figure.png" httpUri-4="https://zenodo.org/record/1050074/files/figure.png" httpUri-5="https://zenodo.org/record/1050076/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
Figs. 
<number box="[1378,1423,1009,1033]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="5.5" valueMax="8.0" valueMin="3.0">3–8</number>
</figureCitation>
). Ventrally, the gena has a posterior ridge, and the mesoventral intercoxal process (P 
<number box="[1082,1097,1045,1069]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="2.0">2</number>
) tapers to a sharp point that is contiguous with a median carina of the metaventrite.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1436,937,1933]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
The male genitalia are usually quite tubular, and have a basic plan similarity; the parameres are characteristic, the left paramere is very small, and located toward the distal end of the main piece, whereas the right paramere has been lost, the paramere setae having their sockets on the main piece (e.g., 
<figureCitation box="[980,1101,1189,1213]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 11" captionStartId="78.[151,264,1606,1629]" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 11. Aedeagi of holotypes." pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
Figs. 
<number box="[1043,1101,1189,1213]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="10.0" valueMax="11.0" valueMin="9.0">9–11</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1436,937,1933]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<bibRefCitation author="Perkins" box="[199,364,1225,1249]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" refString="Perkins, P. D. (1980). Aquatic beetles of the family Hydraenidae in the Western Hemisphere: classification, biogeography and inferred phylogeny (Insecta: Coleoptera). Quaestiones Entomologicae, 16, 3 - 554." type="journal article" year="1980">
Perkins (
<number box="[298,356,1225,1249]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="1980.0">1980</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
established this group based on the dorsal and ventral morphology, and aedeagal structure of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paeminosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">H. paeminosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the only species known at that time. The validity of this group is strongly corroborated by the female genital structure. The female gonocoxite is &quot;divided&quot;, having a weakly sclerotized midlongitudinal area, and is similarly shaped in all females of species in the group (
<figureCitation box="[749,849,1333,1357]" captionStart="FIGURES 148 – 150" captionStartId="176.[151,264,1581,1604]" captionTargetBox="[237,1360,212,1541]" captionTargetId="figure@176.[226,1360,193,1560]" captionTargetPageId="176" captionText="FIGURES 148 – 150. Female terminal abdominal segments of Hydraena species." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1050223/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
Fig. 
<number box="[804,849,1333,1357]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="148.0">148</number>
</figureCitation>
; females are not yet known for 
<taxonomicName box="[1217,1366,1333,1357]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="punctilata">
<emphasis box="[1217,1366,1333,1357]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">H. punctilata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). The spermatheca is circular, somewhat disc-shaped (e.g., 
<figureCitation box="[751,915,1369,1393]" captionStart="FIGURES 151 – 154" captionStartId="177.[151,264,1650,1673]" captionTargetBox="[236,1345,201,1619]" captionTargetId="figure@177.[229,1357,193,1629]" captionTargetPageId="177" captionText="FIGURES 151 – 154. Spermathecae of Hydraena species." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1050225/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
Figs. 
<number box="[815,915,1369,1393]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="153154.0">153, 154</number>
</figureCitation>
) in all species except 
<taxonomicName box="[1166,1322,1370,1393]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paeminosa">
<emphasis box="[1166,1322,1370,1393]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">H. paeminosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, in which the spermatheca has additional lateral lobes (
<figureCitation box="[669,770,1405,1429]" captionStart="FIGURES 155 – 159" captionStartId="178.[151,264,1608,1631]" captionText="FIGURES 155 – 159. Spermathecae of Hydraena species." pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
Fig. 
<number box="[724,770,1405,1429]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="155.0">155</number>
</figureCitation>
). The spermatheca differs markedly from that of all other American 
<taxonomicName box="[268,380,1441,1465]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[268,380,1441,1465]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Hydraena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, except members of the 
<taxonomicName box="[658,753,1442,1465]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="82" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curvosa">
<emphasis box="[658,753,1442,1465]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Curvosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Group. Externally and male genitalically the two groups are quite different.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1436,937,1933]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
Species in this group have been collected primarily from pool habitats. The following habitat information is present in the locality data: small pool on sand bar, edge of sunlit river (
<taxonomicName box="[971,1112,1549,1573]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="boliviana">
<emphasis box="[971,1112,1549,1573]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">H. boliviana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); waterholes from drying up forest stream with gravelly bottom; detrital pools forest; forest creek; pooled detrital creek (
<taxonomicName box="[1175,1330,1586,1609]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paeminosa">
<emphasis box="[1175,1330,1586,1609]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">H. paeminosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); stream, pond (
<taxonomicName box="[223,319,1622,1645]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="xingu">
<emphasis box="[223,319,1622,1645]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">H. xingu</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); in small ponds full of dead leaves, rainforest ridge; flight-intercept pan trap across small stream in forest (
<taxonomicName box="[244,407,1657,1681]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="duohamata">
<emphasis box="[244,407,1657,1681]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">H. duohamata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); along small whitewater stream; pools of dead leaves &amp; sticks; flight-intercept pan trap along open weedy river bank; flight-intercept pan trap in rainforest; flight-intercept pan trap across small stream in forest (
<taxonomicName box="[231,349,1729,1753]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="neblina">
<emphasis box="[231,349,1729,1753]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">H. neblina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1436,937,1933]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
Five of the species are rather closely related, based on the male genitalia and general habitus. 
<taxonomicName box="[1287,1408,1765,1789]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="neblina">
<emphasis box="[1287,1408,1765,1789]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">H. neblina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is quite divergent in both the aedeagus and habitus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1436,937,1933]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
Based on the known distributions, this group appears to be restricted to a circum-Amazonian pattern (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 193 – 194. 193" captionStartId="187.[151,264,1650,1673]" captionTargetBox="[282,1304,193,1628]" captionTargetId="figure@187.[282,1305,193,1629]" captionTargetPageId="187" captionText="FIGURES 193 – 194. 193. Geographical distributions of species in the Paeminosa Group. 194. Geographical distributions of species in the Curvosa and Multispina Groups." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1050236/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
Fig. 
<number box="[151,196,1873,1897]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="193.0">193</number>
</figureCitation>
). The Amazon basin appears to be a &quot;black hole&quot; for 
<taxonomicName box="[796,908,1873,1897]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[796,908,1873,1897]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Hydraena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but this could simply reflect a lack of specialized collecting in that huge area.
</paragraph>
